author: Lawrance 2022
title: The Impact of Climate Change on Mental Health and Emotional Wellbeing: A Narrative Review of Current Evidence, and its Implications
notes:
Narrative review. Focuses on multiple points within our framework and builds their own framework (focusing on socioeconomic, cultural, and environmental factors to lead to "co-beneficial" policy recommendations) to examine the impacts of climate change on people's mental health. Framework categorizes mental health into 5 nested layers interacting with each other and climate change. Cool figures. Breaks down risks of climate change and types of mental health studies by region. Love this paper.
Does discuss eco anxiety as well, but paper has a larger focus on other aspects.

Skews more toward psychological discussions as opposed to environmental factors. Will be complementary to compare our findings to this work.

Discusses climate justice in context of environmental justice

author: Golitaleb 2022
title: Prevalence of Post-traumatic Stress Disorder After Flood: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis
notes:
Might open up an interesting piece of discussion: 
Although disasters occur around the world and are studied
globally, there are intercultural limitations in the use of PTSD
assessment tools that have been originally designed and approved
in developed countries. It is necessary to be more careful about
the inferences that can be drawn from studies using these
tools. Another limitation of this study was that most studies
were performed in Asia, so the generalization of the results
of this study to the whole world may be limited, so it is
recommended that other studies be performed to assess PTSD in
other parts of the world.
